  "question": "In an Adjacency List representation of a graph, how is the list structured?",
  "session_id": "08b59a0a-c5fb-4a30-ae6a-3d4c7eb17f11",
  "answer": "In an **Adjacency List** representation, the graph is stored as:\n\n- an **array of lists**, one list for each vertex\n- for each vertex \\(u\\), `Adjacency[u]` contains all vertices that are **adjacent** to \\(u\\)\n\nSo the structure is:\n\n- **Each vertex has its own list**\n- The list stores the **neighbors** of that vertex\n- In a **directed graph**, the list usually contains the **out-neighbors** only\n- In an **undirected graph**, each edge appears in the lists of **both endpoints**\n\nExample:\n- `Adjacency[u] = v ‚Üí w` means vertex \\(u\\) is connected to \\(v\\) and \\(w\\)",
